The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, Aug. 30: The government will electronically connect 70 ports in the country by the end of next year, a move that will help exporters reduce transaction costs. The commerce ministry is encouraging the use of electronic systems with initiatives such as the electronic data interchange-enabled ports, electronic message exchange between the customs and the directorate general of foreign trade.                             
	 New Delhi, Aug. 30: Globsyn Infotech is in advanced talks with two American companies for acquisition. We are in advanced stage of talks with the two US-based companies for acquisition and my target is to complete at least one by June 30, 2010, said Bikram Dasgupta, chairman of the Calcutta-based IT product and services company.                            
	 London, Aug. 30: The UK arm of Lehman Brothers is preparing a $100-billion claim against its former parent company in the US, according to a report by the Sunday Times. The demand is being finalised by PricewaterhouseCoopers, Lehmans UK administrator, and will be lodged in the next few weeks.                             
	 New Delhi, Aug. 30: Indias healthcare industry has posted a growth of 42.44 per cent in net profit in the first quarter of the current fiscal compared with the year-ago period, Assocham president Sajjan Jindal said.                            
	 Mumbai, Aug. 30: The Institute of Chartered Accountants of India (ICAI) is likely to come out with insurance- specific accounting standards in the next three months, ICAI president Uttam Prakash Agarwal said. A group of experts has been appointed for the purpose.                             
	 Mumbai, Aug. 30: Fraud-hit Satyams restatement of accounts is likely to be completed by the end of December, the companys government-appointed director C. Achuthan has said. Audit firms KPMG and Deloitte are working on restating the firms accounts.                             
	 New Delhi, Aug. 30: Industry has strongly opposed a proposal of developed countries that duty on specific sectors be eliminated under the sectoral initiative of the Doha round of trade talks, according to Ficci.                                                                                                                                     
